and shaming them?

39:33.037 --> 39:35.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOSH BOAK: It's definitely
possible.

39:35.406 --> 39:39.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Business leaders I have talked
to have said
that they expect to have a
bullseye on them.

39:39.177 --> 39:43.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what we have also seen
talking with members
of the Trump transition team is
that Donald

39:43.748 --> 39:48.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump sees these actions and
interventions
as a way to stay connected with
his voting

39:48.319 --> 39:50.054 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
base.

39:50.088 --> 39:53.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Do you think
that these
-- as you mentioned, this is not
necessarily

39:53.258 --> 39:55.059 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a reflection of a new policy.

39:55.093 --> 39:59.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, do you have any sense how
Trump might
-- how this might translate,
these actions

39:59.897 --> 40:04.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
might translate into a more
cohesive economic
policy going forward?

40:04.035 --> 40:07.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BOAK: Well, he ran on the
premise of
America first.

40:07.605 --> 40:11.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was all part of the
greater make
America great again theme.

40:11.276 --> 40:14.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's clearly said that he wants
to increase
manufacturing jobs.

40:14.445 --> 40:16.447 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so this seems to be a
component of that.

40:16.481 --> 40:18.650 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The question is how he goes
about that.

40:18.683 --> 40:22.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We don't have the policy
details, although
he has suggested that he will
impose a border

40:22.854 --> 40:28.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tax of some kind on companies
that move jobs
overseas.

40:28.459 --> 40:32.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's also suggested that he's
going to cut
regulation, which increases
profits for a

40:32.430 --> 40:34.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lot of these companies.

40:34.265 --> 40:38.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What remains to be seen is
whether he can
create jobs on a meaningful
scale and generate

40:38.336 --> 40:43.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the kind of economic growth
that's he's actually
promised, about 3.5 percent a
year.

40:43.341 --> 40:46.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It seems to be
he has got
a carrots-and-sticks policy
going here.

40:46.744 --> 40:51.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's going to offer them,
potentially, less
regulations and thus lower
taxes, and then

40:51.916 --> 40:56.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also threaten to put this tax on
them if they
try to leave the country.

40:56.587 --> 41:01.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you think that there's an
appetite in Congress
to actually put those measures
into place?

41:01.492 --> 41:04.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOSH BOAK: Well, that remains to
be seen.

41:04.862 --> 41:10.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What executives like Ford CEO
Mark Fields
has said when he talks about his
decision

41:11.002 --> 41:16.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on Mexico is to say -- is to
emphasize the
taxes and deregulation.

41:16.407 --> 41:19.744 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is focusing on the carrots,
not the sticks.

41:19.777 --> 41:23.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Business leaders are emphasizing
those carrots,
which means that they either
don't want to

41:23.915 --> 41:26.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
address the sticks or they don't
think the
sticks are likely to happen.

41:26.684 --> 41:29.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You have
obviously been
covering economic policy for a
long time.

41:29.887 --> 41:35.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How unusual is this, to have a
president-elect
naming companies by name and
singling them

41:35.159 --> 41:37.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- singling them out, and then
them responding?

41:37.729 --> 41:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BOAK: It's unprecedented
because he hasn't
assumed office yet.

41:41.766 --> 41:46.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More importantly, he's doing so
on social
media and other venues that
presidents historically

41:46.237 --> 41:47.438 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
have not had.

41:47.472 --> 41:50.174 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Just because
it hasn't existed.

41:50.208 --> 41:51.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSH BOAK: Exactly.

41:51.909 --> 41:55.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Josh Boak, AP,
thank you very much for being
here.

41:55.646 --> 42:02.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSH BOAK: Thank you.

42:02.987 --> 42:10.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: We continue our
look at the
Obama years and his legacy.

42:10.695 --> 42:16.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we focus on a subject
that often
gets less attention, public
education.

42:16.134 --> 42:19.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Much of what happens in the
classroom is decided
at the state and local level.

42:19.837 --> 42:24.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the federal government can
also be a big
player in some of the most
personal issues

42:24.475 --> 42:30.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for families, which is also the
focus of our
weekly segment Making the Grade.

42:30.148 --> 42:36.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Throughout most of his term,
President Obama
and his former education
secretary, Arne Duncan,

42:36.721 --> 42:41.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exercised far more power and
influence in
education than many of their
predecessors.

42:41.692 --> 42:46.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One major focus, a demand for
greater student
testing tied directly to teacher
evaluation

42:46.431 --> 42:49.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and, crucially, federal money
for schools.

42:49.834 --> 42:55.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Duncan was essentially the
gatekeeper of billion
of stimulus money known as Race
to the Top.

42:55.940 --> 42:59.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Districts could qualify if they
agreed to
meet those criteria.

42:59.043 --> 43:01.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Initially, many states joined
in.

43:01.446 --> 43:06.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, over time, resistance began
building
to testing, data-driven metrics,
and whether

43:06.484 --> 43:09.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
teachers were being judged
unfairly.

43:09.353 --> 43:11.456 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The president himself addressed
those concerns.

43:11.489 --> 43:14.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
When we talk about testing,
parents worry

43:14.959 --> 43:19.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that it means more teaching to
the test.

43:19.197 --> 43:23.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some worry that tests are
culturally biased.

43:23.801 --> 43:28.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Teachers worry that they will be
evaluated
solely on the basis of a single
standardized

43:28.339 --> 43:29.307 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
test.

43:29.340 --> 43:32.677 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Everybody thinks that's unfair.

43:32.710 --> 43:34.779 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It is unfair.

43:34.812 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that's not what Race to the
Top is about.

43:36.681 --> 43:39.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What Race to the Top says is,
there's nothing
wrong with testing.

43:39.951 --> 43:44.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We just need better tests
applied in a way
that helps teachers and
students, instead

43:44.489 --> 43:49.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of stifling what teachers and
students do
in the classroom.

43:49.393 --> 43:53.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: It also led to a
backlash
of state standards known as the
Common Core.

43:53.397 --> 43:55.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIA SASS RUBIN, Save Our
Schools New Jersey:
They're impacting the kind of
education kids

43:55.867 --> 43:59.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are getting, because they're
eating up a lot
of introduction time with test
preparation

43:59.971 --> 44:01.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and test drilling.

44:01.873 --> 44:07.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: On this issue, we are
shoulder to shoulder,
parents, conservatives,
progressives, the

44:07.879 --> 44:09.647 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
teachers.

44:09.680 --> 44:13.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're all opposed to this
because this is
not about learning, this is not
about education.

44:13.217 --> 44:17.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALISON STEWART: The
administration promoted
the expansion of charter
schools, and pointed

44:17.288 --> 44:20.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to a national graduation rate
topping 83 percent.

44:21.025 --> 44:24.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
At the same time, the
president's team took
a bigger role in higher
education.

44:24.929 --> 44:29.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It became the direct lender to
students, instead
of having the loans made
directly by banks.

44:29.867 --> 44:32.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Savings were used to expand Pell
Grants.

44:32.737 --> 44:37.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the administration took aim
at the world
of for-profit colleges, cracking
down on federal

44:37.308 --> 44:43.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
funds and contending that
students were frequently
not well-served by the schools.

44:43.648 --> 44:47.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's dig a little deeper into
the Obama legacy
in education with two people who
have covered

44:47.418 --> 44:53.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it extensively, Alyson Klein of
our partners
at Education Week, and Scott
Jaschik of Inside

44:53.090 --> 44:54.592 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Higher Ed.

44:54.625 --> 44:56.627 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thanks to both of you for being
here.

44:56.661 --> 45:00.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's talk about what the Obama
administration
wanted to do when it first got
into office.

45:00.765 --> 45:04.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Alyson, what was one thing that
they wanted
to tackle about through K-12
education immediately?

45:04.669 --> 45:09.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN, Education Week:
So, they were
in a very fortunate position
when they first

45:09.206 --> 45:14.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
came into office, in that the
Obama administration
was given $100 billion for
education through

45:14.946 --> 45:18.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the American Recovery and
Reinvestment Act,
better known as the stimulus.

45:18.716 --> 45:22.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And with some of that money
through a program
known as Race to the Top, they
were able to

45:22.353 --> 45:27.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prod states to adopt college and
career-ready
standards, better known as the
Common Core,

45:27.525 --> 45:32.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
new forms of teacher evaluation
that relied
in part on student test scores,
and dramatic

45:32.129 --> 45:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ways of turning around the
lowest performing
schools, including getting rid
of principals

45:36.500 --> 45:37.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and many teachers.

45:37.902 --> 45:40.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: All right, we
will unpack
that in a little bit.

45:40.404 --> 45:42.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Same question for you, Scott,
about higher
education.

45:42.607 --> 45:44.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What did the Obama
administration wanted to
tackle right away?

45:44.642 --> 45:46.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SCOTT JASCHIK, Inside Higher
Education: Sure.

45:46.510 --> 45:50.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In President Obama's first state
of the union,
he said something no president
had said before,

45:50.047 --> 45:56.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is that every American
needs at least
one year of post-secondary
training to succeed

45:56.387 --> 45:58.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in today's economy.

45:58.222 --> 46:02.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you see that priority
reflected in much
that the administration did,
proposals for

46:02.593 --> 46:08.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
free community college, putting
more money
into aid for low-income
students.

46:08.733 --> 46:13.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The key difference between past
administrations
is that I would say,
historically, the focus

46:13.671 --> 46:18.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of higher ed policy has been on
helping middle-class
families who were already going
to send their

46:18.442 --> 46:22.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
children to college to do so in
more affordable
ways.

46:22.246 --> 46:27.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama focused on the
students who
weren't going, those who needed
higher education,

46:27.952 --> 46:30.488 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but were not seeking it.

46:30.521 --> 46:32.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: Alyson, let's
unpack a little
bit of what you talked about.

46:32.957 --> 46:39.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Testing became a buzzword among
K-12 education,
associated with Common Core
state standards.

46:39.830 --> 46:44.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Common Core was obviously an
idea, a way
to have a federal standard, so
that students

46:44.201 --> 46:47.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Nevada could be compared to
students in
Texas.

46:47.638 --> 46:52.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What happened in theory with
Common Core and
testing vs. what happened in
practice?

46:52.143 --> 46:56.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: So, the Obama
administration
didn't tell states that they had
to adopt

46:56.280 --> 47:00.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Common Core standards, but
they did give
them, a number of states, money
who chose

47:00.851 --> 47:02.586 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to do that.

47:02.620 --> 47:05.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they also used some of the
money from
the stimulus which I talked
about to help

47:05.690 --> 47:10.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
states develop new, more
innovative forms
of tests aligned with those
standards.

47:10.728 --> 47:13.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they were really demanding a
lot from
states at once.

47:13.731 --> 47:18.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Teach had to adjust to brand-new
standards
that were much more rigorous in
many cases

47:18.035 --> 47:20.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than the standards they had
before and brand-new
types of tests.

47:20.905 --> 47:23.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it just put a lot of
pressure on a system.

47:23.908 --> 47:26.010 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: And also on
teacher evaluations.

47:26.043 --> 47:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That became a very difficult
subject, because
you had teachers in certain
schools with certain

47:31.315 --> 47:35.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sort of support and scaffolding
being compared
to teachers in other schools
perhaps in more

47:35.986 --> 47:36.954 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
affluent areas.

47:36.987 --> 47:38.956 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: Yes, that's right.

47:38.989 --> 47:43.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the big issues with
teacher evaluation
is that teachers felt that it
didn't necessarily

47:43.327 --> 47:47.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reward them for taking on more
challenging
groups of students.

47:47.098 --> 47:51.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as I mentioned before, the
tests and
the standards were changing at
the same time

47:51.736 --> 47:54.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that teacher performance was
being held to
those tests.

47:54.371 --> 47:57.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, they really felt like that
was an unfair
situation for them.

47:57.174 --> 48:01.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: Charter schools
was another
big part of the Obama
administration's push.

48:01.412 --> 48:06.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I believe there was something
like $208 million
for charter schools in
2008-2009.

48:06.584 --> 48:10.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's up to $333 million,
approximately,
now.

48:10.287 --> 48:11.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Why the focus on charter
schools?

48:11.956 --> 48:15.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: So, charter
schools are one
of the few areas of K-12
education policy

48:15.693 --> 48:19.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where Democrats and Republicans
really see
eye to eye for the most part.

48:19.663 --> 48:24.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Obama administration in
particular really
pushed states that had lowest --
low-performing

48:24.068 --> 48:27.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
schools to consider turning
those schools
into a charter.

48:27.538 --> 48:31.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they also asked states to
set a high bar
for charters, make sure that
charters were

48:31.108 --> 48:35.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
serving all different kinds of
students, students
in special education and
English-language

48:35.346 --> 48:40.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
learners, and were being held to
the same
standards as regular public
schools.

48:40.151 --> 48:41.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: Scott, let's
bring you into
the conversation.

48:41.619 --> 48:43.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SCOTT JASCHIK: Sure.

48:43.420 --> 48:48.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: You mentioned
bringing new
people into the higher education
population.

48:48.425 --> 48:51.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How did the president and his
administration
make this possible?

48:51.328 --> 48:55.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Were they successful with
bringing people
in to the higher population,
higher education

48:55.666 --> 48:57.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
population that wouldn't have
been there before?

48:57.301 --> 49:00.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SCOTT JASCHIK: Many times, they
were successful,
but not the way he proposed it.

49:00.805 --> 49:01.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: What does that
mean?

49:01.839 --> 49:03.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SCOTT JASCHIK: So, take free
community college.

49:03.774 --> 49:09.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama proposed a
state-federal partnership
that would make community
college free.

49:09.246 --> 49:10.414 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Congress never touched it.

49:10.447 --> 49:13.384 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you could say, on one hand,
nothing happened.

49:13.417 --> 49:19.256 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the reality is that
districts all over
the country took the idea and
ran with it.

49:19.290 --> 49:23.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so there are free community
college programs
in individual districts all over
the country.

49:23.627 --> 49:30.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Also, I would say, by talking
about the issue,
President Obama put much more
emphasis on

49:30.134 --> 49:34.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that choice than you ever saw
before.

49:34.038 --> 49:38.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
President Obama and also
Michelle Obama used
their bully pulpits to say, hey,
it's important

49:38.876 --> 49:40.678 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to go.

49:40.711 --> 49:45.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they said -- they linked it
over and over
again to jobs that students
would need for

49:45.115 --> 49:46.350 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the future.

49:46.383 --> 49:49.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in that sense, I think he
changed the
conversation.

49:49.186 --> 49:52.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Community colleges used to be
sort of a side
issue.

49:52.423 --> 49:54.959 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He made them much more central.

49:54.992 --> 49:58.829 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He also focused a lot on
endorsing alternative
ways to go to college.

49:58.863 --> 50:04.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's a fan of online education,
competency-based
education, all kinds of new
approaches that,

50:04.602 --> 50:09.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
again, he used the bully pulpit
to promote,
not so much federal legislation,
but with

50:09.907 --> 50:11.175 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
attention.

50:11.208 --> 50:13.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: How about
dealing with income
inequality?

50:13.410 --> 50:16.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We see that in secondary
education.

50:16.413 --> 50:19.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kids who come from well-to-do
families often
go to college.

50:19.316 --> 50:23.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a very small percentage of
people who
come from lower-income families.

50:23.420 --> 50:25.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What did he do and his
administration do to
help those folks?

50:25.723 --> 50:31.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT JASCHIK: So, early on, he
promoted large
increases -- and he got some --
in Pell Grants,

50:31.228 --> 50:35.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is the largest federal
program for low-income
students.

50:35.199 --> 50:39.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He wasn't thrilled with the
results, though,
because a lot of the money ended
up going

50:39.103 --> 50:43.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to students at for-profit
institutions, where
he questioned the quality.

50:43.641 --> 50:48.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think that's part of what
led him to
free community college, to focus
attention

50:48.512 --> 50:51.048 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on another sector.

50:51.081 --> 50:54.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He also focused a lot on the
quality of institutions.

50:54.818 --> 50:59.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He wasn't, you know, looking at
community
colleges through rose-colored
glasses.

50:59.423 --> 51:04.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He talked about the need for
them to improve
their graduation rates, to
improve their -- the

51:04.094 --> 51:06.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
connection between their job
training programs
and actual careers.

51:06.931 --> 51:11.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he was putting attention
there, not on
Harvard and Stanford.

51:11.802 --> 51:14.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: What about
attention about
what's going on, on campus?

51:14.505 --> 51:19.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were so many stories about
sexual assault
issues on campuses in the past
year-and-a-half.

51:19.710 --> 51:24.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT JASCHIK: I think this is
an area where
the Obama administration played
a very significant

51:24.048 --> 51:25.749 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
role.

51:25.783 --> 51:29.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One, they talked about it a lot,
not just
the Education Department, but
President Obama,

51:29.653 --> 51:32.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Vice President Biden, in
repeated events.

51:32.256 --> 51:35.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They also, the administration
changed the
rules.

51:35.526 --> 51:40.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They told colleges to change the
burden of
proof when colleges were
considering these

51:40.965 --> 51:44.468 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cases, saying it had to only be
a preponderance
of evidence.

51:44.501 --> 51:49.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that's a lower standard
than, say, guilty
beyond a reasonable doubt.

51:49.606 --> 51:54.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they empowered the Office
for Civil Rights
at the Education Department to
have resources

51:54.845 --> 52:02.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do more investigations, so,
attention and
policy, at the same time that
activists on

52:02.820 --> 52:05.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
campuses were raising the issue
more than
ever.

52:05.122 --> 52:08.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: A final question
for both
of you.

52:08.092 --> 52:14.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What do you think will be the
lasting impact
of his education legacy, the
thing that will

52:14.064 --> 52:18.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stick around, regardless of
what's going on
in terms of politics?

52:18.302 --> 52:20.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: That's a great
question.

52:20.337 --> 52:25.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would say one of the big
focuses of the
administration was on turning
around the lowest-performing

52:25.943 --> 52:27.644 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
schools.

52:27.678 --> 52:30.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's something that's been
enshrined
in a law called the Every
Student Succeeds

52:30.647 --> 52:32.349 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Act.

52:32.383 --> 52:35.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States will still have to focus
on schools
that are just at the bottom of
the barrel

52:35.586 --> 52:37.287 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
when it comes to performers.

52:37.321 --> 52:39.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's something that I
expect to continue
no matter who's in the White
House.

52:40.024 --> 52:41.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALISON STEWART: What do you
think, Scott?

52:41.725 --> 52:45.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT JASCHIK: I would say this
